Bank served the Dutch ministery of Colonies and consequently followed Dutch trade interests, the bank's history intersects with the history of slavery. The investigation in this book focuses not only upon DNB's formal involvement but also on the private involvement of its directors. In addition, it examines whether the bank and its directors played any role in the abolition of slavery."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAntislavery movements. 0aSlave tradezUnited StatesxFinance. 0aSlaveryxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 4aColonial Studies. 4aDutch and The Netherlands. 4aHistory. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aSlavery, Dutch history, Economic history, Central Banks, Colonial history.1 aLauret, Lauren, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aTol, Joris, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789400604384zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789400604384/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA